               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18470614-1501-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1501-18470614 t18470614-1501-offence-1 t18470614-1501-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>1501. <persName id="def1-1501-18470614" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1501-18470614" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1501-18470614" type="age" value="25"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1501-18470614" type="surname" value="STEVENS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1501-18470614" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">HENRY STEVENS</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted<rs id="t18470614-1501-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470614-1501-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="deception"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470614-1501-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="fraud"></interp> for unlawfully obtaining goods by false pretences.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-961" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-961" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-961" type="surname" value="BROCKING"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-961" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM BROCKING</persName>
                  </hi>. I am in the service of William Watt, a grocer, of Park-terrace, Liverpool-road. On the 10th of May the prisoner came to the shop, he said he was in the service of William Hunt, and asked me to show him some shoe-brushes—I showed him a box containing several—he took three—he asked me the price—I said, "1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. each"—he said, "Put them down to my <hi rend="italic">governor</hi>, you know who I mean"—I said, "You mean Hunt, across the way?"—he said. "Yes"—that is Mr. Hunt, a stable-keeper—he took the brushes away—on the afternoon of the same day he came again, and brought the brushes back, saying he would exchange them for three others, as Mr. Hunt supposed the first expense would be the least, and he would have a better quality—he then asked for a body-brush for the bodies and insides of carriages—he asked me the price—I told him they were marked outside—he had four brushes, three in exchange, and one extra—he said he would exchange them for Hunt, and that his master would come in the course of the week and settle for them—he took them away with him—he gave me his name, as Harry Smith—when he came a second time, he said, "It is cus<lb></lb>tomary for us men to have an invoice, merely to show our employer—I gave it him—on Friday, the 14th, he came again for a bottle of blacking—he took up a bottle of blacking, saying, "Add this to the brushes," and took it away.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BALLANTINE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Are Messrs. Wood and Hunt in partnership? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, and were at this time—he said, "My governor," not "governors"—I am sure of that, because I said, "Hunt," and he said, "Yes"—I had seen him so often at Mr. Hunt's house, that I thought him the servant—I might have thought it suspicious if he had come the second time without returning the first set—it is very probable I might have asked him some question, or gone and made inquiry—he said, "No doubt Mr. Hunt will come on Saturday night, or to-morrow, or between this and Saturday, and pay for them"—Mr. Watt is in business alone—his Christian name is William.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-962" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-962" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-962" type="surname" value="COLLINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-962" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN COLLINS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a sergeant of police at Enfield. On Sunday, the 16th of May, between twelve and one o'clock at night, I saw the prisoner at a public-house at Enfield, quarrelling about a dog—I observed his person, and asked him what he had got in his pocket—he refused to tell me—he after<lb></lb>wards said they were brushes—I asked where he got them—he refused to ay—I took him to the station, and found four brushes and a bottle of</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184706140168"></xptr>
               <p>blacking in his pocket—he said he had purchased them to bring to Enfield to make them a present to his father; that he had been in the employ of a livery. stable keeper in the Liverpool-road, and had bought them at Mr. Watts' shop, he took the bill out of a purse in his pocket—I looked at it and said, "This is not a bill of these brushes, but a bill of Mr. Smith to Mr. Watts, and I know your name to be Stevens"—he said the master's name was Watts, and the man's name was Smith.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Is it true that he refused to tell you where he got them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—he refused to give me a satisfactory account—I said so before the Magistrate, but do not see it in my depositions—it is not there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470614-name-963" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-963" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-963" type="surname" value="HUNT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470614-name-963" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE HUNT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a livery-stable keeper, and live at Islington. I also have two places, one in John-street, and the other in Barnsbury-street, Islington—the prisoner had been in my service a fortnight when he left me—I never sent him to Mr. Watts for blacking or brushes, or authorized him to get any.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> If you wanted brushes would there be a great crime in a man going and getting them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, without my orders—my men have not done so during the twelve years I have been in business—I never allow any one to get anything on credit, or in my name—Mr. Wood is in part<lb></lb>nership with me—I call it my place, because I live there—my name is George.</p>
               <p>
